The Telegraph - Calcutta : International

 UK man to hang in Pak

 Hussain: Devastated

 Islamabad, July 21 (Reuters): A British man convicted of killing a taxi driver in Pakistan has been put on death row for a third time and will be hanged on August 3, relatives and officials said today.

 Mirza Tahir Hussain, 36, who is of Pakistani descent, has twice had his execution stayed on the intervention of President Pervez Musharraf. His family was given one months time from June 1 to reach a settlement with the relatives of the dead man.

 A judge in Islamabad issued new death warrants for Hussain after his family failed to reach a settlement with the heirs of the victim., a prison official in Rawalpindi city where he is being held, said.

 The deceaseds family have broken all contact with us and turned down our heavy blood money offer, Hussains brother, Amjad Hussain said by telephone from London.

 We are devastated and traumatised after being told Tahir is to be executed on August 3, he said. 




